![](https://globalvoices.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/12-09-2011-Burundian-
Troop-Rotation-Mogadshu-Airport____AMISOM-Public-
Information_Flickr-800x534-1.jpg)

Burundian African Union troops arrive at Mogadishu Airport, Somalia, December
9, 2011. AMISOM Public Information via Flickr / Creative Commons.

Since 2007, [AMISOM,](http://amisom-au.org/key-documents/united-nations-
security-council-resolutions/) the African Union (AU) mission in Somalia, has
been tasked with combating Al-Shabaab, an extremist Islamist militant group
with ties to Al-Qaeda. Many
[hundreds](https://theglobalobservatory.org/2015/09/amisom-african-union-
somalia-peacekeeping/) of soldiers have died among troops totaling 21,500 from
several different
[countries,](https://www.tandfonline.com/doi/abs/10.1080/17531055.2018.1418159?journalCode=rjea20)
with Burundi having the second largest troops after Uganda.

In December 2018, the AU's Peace and Security Council decided to withdraw
1,000 of their 5,400 Burundian soldiers from Somalia by late February 2019, as
part of the [progressive](https://www.un.org/press/fr/2017/cs12972.doc.htm)
[reduction](https://www.dailymaverick.co.za/article/2019-02-28-is-this-the-
right-time-to-downsize-amisom/) of AMISOM military decided by the United
Nations Security Council in July 2018. UN
[resolution](https://www.un.org/press/en/2018/sc13439.doc.htm) 2431 extended
AMISOM’s mandate but determined to reduce troop numbers and eventually hand
over the conflict to Somali forces by December 2021.

[Burundian President Nkurunziza objected](https://www.softpower.ug/nkurunziza-
protests-aus-plan-to-exclusively-withdraw-burundi-amisom-troops/) to the
[withdrawal](http://www.iwacu-burundi.org/rapatriement-des-troupes-de-lamisom-
lassemblee-nationale-dit-toujours-non/) while
[officials](https://twitter.com/dndabarushimana/status/1093785171785068545)
called it dangerous for regional security and [protested to the
AU.](http://www.rtnb.bi/fr/art.php?idapi=3/0/210) Burundi parliamentarians
[particularly objected](http://www.iwacu-burundi.org/amisom-bujumbura-deboute-
mais/) to [only](https://www.softpower.ug/nkurunziza-protests-aus-plan-to-
exclusively-withdraw-burundi-amisom-troops/) Burundian troop reductions and
none from other countries. They suggested the threat of
[withdrawing](https://allafrica.com/stories/201902250570.html) [all their
troops](https://m.facebook.com/sosmediasburundi/photos/a.914236618638378/2236069066455120/?type=3&source=57)
if the AU didn't reconsider the decision. Parliamentarians even spoke of plots
and attempt to “destabilize” Burundi.

Burundi’s government had
[proposed](https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-02-22/burundi-
threatens-to-withdraw-all-its-troops-from-somalia) to share the troop
withdrawal with other states, as in a previous troop reduction in December
2017.

