During the Somali president Mohamed Abdullahi Mohamed's
[visit](https://twitter.com/BdiPresidence/status/1097818292188794880) to
Burundi in mid-February, both presidents called for a
[summit](https://www.jeuneafrique.com/738032/politique/retrait-des-troupes-
burundaises-de-lamisom-le-burundi-et-la-somalie-demandent-un-sommet-urgent/)
in a joint
[communique](https://twitter.com/BurundiGov/status/1097824722279108608) to
review the issue. Nevertheless, on February 21 and 23, 400 Burundian soldiers
[returned](http://www.rfi.fr/afrique/20190224-somalie-amisom-ua-retrait-
soldats-burundais-retour) home, although the Burundian government
[refused](https://afriqueconfidentielle.com/politique/diplomatie/somalie-
burundi-ne-sopposerait-plus-retrait-de-troupes/) to proceed with withdrawing
the [remaining](http://www.iwacu-burundi.org/rapatriement-des-troupes-de-
lamisom-lassemblee-nationale-dit-toujours-non/) 600, originally planned to be
completed by February 26.

On February 28, Burundi’s government [eventually
relented](https://information.tv5monde.com/afrique/le-burundi-aurait-renonce-
s-opposer-au-retrait-de-ses-troupes-de-somalie-287578), lacking support or
leverage on the issue, and that the remaining soldiers would return in early
March, according to high-level anonymous sources of AFP, cited by TV5Monde.

