### Why does Burundi object to AMISOM's troop reduction?

Burundi's ongoing political and economic crisis has led to serious budget
shortfalls related to sanctions, exacerbated
[poverty](https://www.crisisgroup.org/fr/africa/central-
africa/burundi/264-soutenir-la-population-burundaise-face-la-crise-
economique), trade disruption and large
[refugee](http://www.rfi.fr/afrique/20190221-le-cri-alarme-humanitaires-
situation-refugies-burundais)
[movements.](https://www.lemonde.fr/afrique/article/2018/12/03/les-refugies-
burundais-victimes-sans-fin-d-une-crise-
oubliee_5392118_3212.html?fbclid=IwAR3fuMxE-
RHsoRJNJjwFKNIvds9AUXFeMCLRG0j6GMt26-jp1g0Gd8DsBFE) Last year, the UN Security
Council expressed [concern](https://news.un.org/fr/story/2018/08/1021862) for
the humanitarian situation — citing 3.6 million people in need of assistance
in Burundi.

Funding from international peacekeeping missions is, therefore, a significant
[source](https://www.crisisgroup.org/africa/central-africa/burundi/african-
union-and-burundi-crisis-ambition-versus-reality) of foreign currency for the
embattled government. Jeune Afrique reported the AU
[transfers](https://www.jeuneafrique.com/738032/politique/retrait-des-troupes-
burundaises-de-lamisom-le-burundi-et-la-somalie-demandent-un-sommet-urgent/)
16 million euros every 3 months to Burundi’s Central Bank.

The EU – a major funder of AMISOM – tried in 2017 to [avoid](http://www.iwacu-
burundi.org/les-eurodeputes-favorables-a-la-fin-des-missions-de-maintien-de-
la-paix-des-militaires-burundais/) passing the funds for soldiers’ salaries
and equipment directly via the government, which takes a percentage
[ostensibly](https://www.crisisgroup.org/africa/central-
africa/burundi/247-burundi-army-crisis) for equipment and other expenditure.
This led to a standoff until an agreement was reached, although RFI reported
soldiers accusing the government of
[appropriation.](http://www.rfi.fr/afrique/20170623-burundi-pouvoir-preleve-
encore-20-salaires-soldats-amisom)

Observers such as anti-corruption [campaigner](http://www.olucome.bi/) Gabriel
Rufyiri see a connection between the request for Burundi to reduce its troops
and its ongoing tensions with the EU, and discontent from East African
Community (EAC) and AU politicians, particularly
[Uganda](http://www.rfi.fr/afrique/20181215-president-ougandais-voit-rouge-
apres-lettre-president-nkurunziza-burundi), over the
[failure](http://www.rfi.fr/afrique/20190201-burundi-sommet-eac-afrique-
grands-lacs-museveni-nkurunziza-mkapa) of mediated dialogue.

This dialogue intended to resolve the grinding political crisis surrounding
Nkurunziza’s controversial third term in 2015, and subsequent constitutional
changes. Burundi’s government intransigence is seen as heavily responsible —
along with weak international engagement — for the dialogue
[struggling](http://www.iwacu-burundi.org/lopposition-en-exil-fachee-contre-
les-presidents-magufuli-et-museveni/) to get started. Burundi did not even
attend the last round in late 2018.

Since 2015, many
[organizations](https://www.amnesty.org/en/latest/news/2018/04/burundi-32-year-
sentence-for-defending-human-rights-an-insult-to-justice/), including the UN
[Commission](https://www.ohchr.org/Documents/HRBodies/HRCouncil/CoIBurundi/ReportHRC39/A_HRC_39_63_EN.pdf)
of Inquiry, [Human Rights Watch](https://www.hrw.org/news/2018/04/17/burundi-
repression-linked-presidential-term-vote), or
[APRODH](http://www.aprodhasbl.org/2018/01/31/890/), documented systematic
rights abuses — especially against the opposition — clampdowns on
[media](https://globalvoices.org/2016/02/16/burundis-independent-media-finds-
itself-in-the-crossfire-of-a-deadly-crisis/) and nongovernmental groups and
clashes with rebel groups. Officials [reject](http://www.iwacu-
burundi.org/droits-de-lhomme-de-nouveau-sur-la-sellette-bujumbura-crie-au-
complot/) reports as manipulated.

In response, the EU and other international partners implemented sanctions and
cut direct aid to the government — which it heavily relied on — seeking to
redirect it to NGOs on the ground. These organizations have found themselves
under increased government [control](http://www.iwacu-burundi.org/suspension-
des-onge-25-deja-reenregistrees-11-autres-en-attente/) and pressure. In
particular, new rules in late 2018 on financing and ethnic quotas prompted
some, like [Handicap International](http://www.rfi.fr/afrique/20190108-ong-
handicap-international-quitte-regret-burundi), to leave the country.

### **Future security**

The troops’ return raises serious questions about security both in Somalia and
in Burundi.

First, a troop reduction may spark potential problems for Burundi's military.
Dangerous peacekeeping missions are better paid and more attractive as
opportunities for soldiers. Many could be discontented with losing the AMISOM
prospect, which could aggravate politicized
[divisions](https://www.crisisgroup.org/africa/central-
africa/burundi/247-burundi-army-crisis) within the army originating in
Burundi's civil war.

Second, critics point to an apparent contradiction in Burundi's government
sending troops to improve foreign citizens’ safety while the human rights
situation at home has deteriorated, with arbitrary arrests, torture and
killings. Burundian blogger Apollinaire Nkurunziza
[reported](https://www.yaga-burundi.com/2018/06/06/amisom-ne-nous-abandonnez-
pas/) that on the ground in Somalia, however, locals have shown appreciation
for Burundian troops.

Controversy occurred, however, over AMISOM soldiers
[accused](https://www.theguardian.com/global-development/2018/nov/09/inquiry-
launched-as-four-men-allegedly-shot-dead-by-peacekeepers-in-somalia-amisom-
roadside-bombing) of killing civilians.

Third, while AMISOM’s eventual [aim](http://www.iwacu-burundi.org/somalie-
vers-une-armee-et-une-police-sans-amisom/) is to [withdraw](http://www.iwacu-
burundi.org/retrait-de-lamisom-un-processus-graduel-et-responsable/) and hand
over to Somali forces, there are
[concerns](http://www.rfi.fr/afrique/20180302-somalie-forces-amisom-retrait-
financement-ua-contributeur)
[over](https://www.dailymaverick.co.za/article/2019-02-28-is-this-the-right-
time-to-downsize-amisom/) [capacity](http://www.iwacu-burundi.org/amisom-une-
resolution-plus-motivee-par-des-facteurs-externes/) and
[future](https://www.yaga-burundi.com/2018/06/06/amisom-ne-nous-abandonnez-
pas/) [stability](https://www.voanews.com/a/somali-troops-against-al-
shabab/4566398.html), including [some](http://www.iwacu-burundi.org/amisom-
bujumbura-deboute-mais/) from Somali officials. Al-Shabaab still
[controls](https://www.news24.com/Africa/News/explainer-who-are-al-shabaab-
attackers-of-kenya-hotel-20190117) territory and can launch
[deadly](https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/africa/somalia-attack-
alshabab-gun-bombing-interior-ministry-mogadishu-a8436071.html)
[attacks](https://www.theeastafrican.co.ke/news/africa/Huge-explosion-rocks-
Mogadishu/4552902-4752342-fqh7bi/index.html), including outside Somalia,
notably [Kenya](https://www.news24.com/Africa/News/explainer-who-are-al-
shabaab-attackers-of-kenya-hotel-20190117).

This episode seems to reflect ongoing tensions with EU and EAC governments
over Burundi’s crisis. [Regional](http://www.iwacu-burundi.org/ces-burundais-
indesirables-dans-la-sous-region/) governments are not
[united](http://www.rfi.fr/afrique/20190204-analyse-22-election-rdc-felix-
tshisekedi-face-grand-jeu-regional) either, and the government has repeatedly
faced off with the EU, AU, and International Criminal Court, among others,
over rights abuses and dialogue with opponents. The CNARED Burundian
opposition coalition in exile has also [suffered](http://www.iwacu-
burundi.org/cnared-des-elections-sur-fond-des-divisions/) further
[divisions](https://www.crisisgroup.org/crisiswatch/january-2019#burundi).

More standoffs could occur, then, as the political-economic crisis continues –
with hundreds of thousands still in underfunded
[refugee](https://globalvoices.org/2017/10/10/burundian-refugees-face-a-
difficult-choice-stay-in-overburdened-camps-or-return-to-uncertainty/) camps
and proxy conflicts in eastern DRC – and new elections in 2020 are fast
approaching.

